% spi_simple.nw -- minimal FPGA->MP135 QUADSPI mission chapter.

== Why this chapter exists

The earlier spi/spi_1lane_stream/spi_quad chapters grew during
debug to ~6000 lines covering pin-walk preflights, debug-UART
reporters, four diagnostic opcodes, MDMA inner-loop logging, DLYB
sweeps, presc/sshift matrices, and ~20 dead-end HDL hypotheses.
None of that is intrinsic to streaming bytes off an FPGA into the
STM32MP135 QUADSPI peripheral. The slave is a shift register; the
master is one peripheral configured for indirect read; the test is
"send a known byte stream, count mismatches." This chapter is the
chapter we wish we had written first: one slave RTL, two mission
blocks, one verifier.

The chapter intentionally does not re-derive the proven SCLK
prescalers, DLYB taps, or sshift values. Those came out of the
spi_quad sweep and live in this chapter as constants:
1-lane mission point is `presc=5 sshift=1` (108.7 MHz wall-rate
107 Mbps over 32 MiB) and quad mission point is `presc=3 sshift=0`
(164 MHz SCLK, 337 Mbps single-pass, firsterr=-1 reproducible
across iter-77/78 sweeps). Lower prescalers were tried and
documented to fail (presc=2 hangs the peripheral; presc=1 returns
HAL_TIMEOUT). The mission floors are conservatively set at
100 Mbps (1-lane) and 200 Mbps (quad) -- both well below the
proven numbers so a single rig hiccup does not turn the chapter
red. See the table in section "Why quad is not 4x single" below.

== Slave RTL: the shift register

A SPI slave is a shift register. CS_n low arms it. On every SCLK
posedge, the slave sees the master sample its output bit (or
nibble in quad). The slave then advances its internal byte counter
and presents the next bit/nibble before the next sample. In quad
mode, two SCLK periods walk one byte (high nibble first, then low
nibble). Mode 0 (CPOL=0 CPHA=0) means data updates on falling
SCLK and is sampled on rising SCLK.

The minimum-viable Verilog is below. It is functionally identical
to the LANES=1 / LANES=4 variants in src/spi.nw -- same byte
sequence, same SB_IO falling-edge update, same async-CS reset to
byte zero -- but written without the test-debug instrumentation,
the START_DELAY hook, the IO2/IO3-pinned-low-in-1-lane workaround,
or the genvar branch for the IO drivers. The source-of-truth
bitstreams (`spi_1lane.bin`, `spi_quad.bin`) come from the
existing src/spi.nw chunks because those are the binaries the
mission was measured against; this Verilog is reproduced here as
documentation, not built.

<<spi_simple_slave.v>>=
// Documentation-only. The mission bitstreams come from src/spi.nw.
module spi_slave #(parameter LANES = 1) (
   input        cs_n,
   input        sclk,
   inout  [3:0] io
);
   reg [7:0] data_byte;
   reg [2:0] phase;     // 0..7 in 1-lane, 0..1 in quad
   wire      oe = ~cs_n;
   wire [3:0] dout;

   always @(posedge cs_n or posedge sclk) begin
      if (cs_n) begin
         data_byte <= 8'd0;
         phase     <= 3'd0;
      end else begin
         if (LANES == 4) begin
            phase <= phase ^ 3'd1;            // 0,1,0,1,...
            if (phase[0]) data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
         end else begin
            phase <= phase + 3'd1;            // 0..7
            if (phase == 3'd7) data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
         end
      end
   end

   assign dout = (LANES == 4)
      ? (phase[0] ? data_byte[7:4] : data_byte[3:0])  // high nibble first
      : {3'b0, data_byte[3'd7 - phase]};              // MSB first, bit-banged onto IO0

   genvar g;
   generate for (g = 0; g < 4; g = g + 1) begin : g_io
      SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b100101), .NEG_TRIGGER(1'b1)) iob (
         .PACKAGE_PIN(io[g]),
         .OUTPUT_CLK(sclk),
         .OUTPUT_ENABLE(oe),
         .D_OUT_0((LANES == 4) ? dout[g] : (g < 2 ? dout[0] : 1'b0))
      );
   end endgenerate
endmodule
@

== Why quad is not 4x single

The user's intuition (quad = 4x single at the wire) is correct
in principle. On this rig it does not hold because the bottleneck
is not the wire -- it is the **AXI bus handshake** the MDMA pays
on every word read from `QUADSPI->DR`. Empirically verified
2026-05-02 with 16 firmware variants in `agent4/kerck_probe/`:
the per-byte overhead is paced by AXI/ACLK at ~3 cycles per byte
(~11.5 ns at AXI=266.5 MHz baseline), independent of CK_QSPI
(PLL4), HCLK6 (PLL3/MLAHB), MDMA TLEN, MDMA SBURST (4/8/16-beat
bursts don't help), or QSPI FTHRES. The model
`T_byte = T_sclk_byte + 3/AXI` fits all 4 AXI scan points
(266.5/133/88.8/66.6 MHz) within a few nanoseconds, and fits all
prescaler points (3,4,5,63 quad).

Measurements at PLL4 = 656 MHz (CK_QSPI):

| presc | SCLK     | 1-lane theory  / measured  | quad theory  / measured       | quad efficiency |
|-------|----------|----------------------------|-------------------------------|-----------------|
| 5     | 109 MHz  | 109 / 107 Mbps  (98%)      | 437 / 268 Mbps                | 61%             |
| 4     | 131 MHz  |   --                       | 525 / 298 Mbps  (firsterr=445)|  alignment fails|
| 3     | 164 MHz  |   --                       | 656 / 337 Mbps  firsterr=-1   | 51% (best clean)|
| 2     | 218 MHz  |   --                       | hangs the peripheral          |   --            |
| 1     | 328 MHz  |   --                       | HAL_TIMEOUT                   |   --            |

Two effects compound:

1. The peripheral's internal pipeline cannot drain the FIFO at
   four bits per CK_QSPI tick once SCLK goes above ~150 MHz. In
   1-lane the wire is the bottleneck, so 98% of theoretical is
   reachable. In quad the peripheral throttles via FTHRES, so
   wall-rate caps out around 270-340 Mbps regardless of
   prescaler.

2. STM32MP135F datasheet Table 76 (verified in
   /tmp/STM32MP135F_datasheet.pdf) caps QUADSPI SDR SCLK at
   166 MHz at 2.7 V <= VDD < 3.6 V (CL = 20 pF), or 90 MHz at
   1.71 V < VDD <= 3.6 V (CL = 15 pF). Neither matches the
   "133 MHz" figure asked about; presc=3 (164 MHz) is at the
   high-VDD ceiling, presc=4 (131 MHz) is below it, and the
   alignment failure at presc=4 is therefore a peripheral-internal
   skew issue rather than a datasheet violation.

Reaching 400 Mbps quad on this peripheral would need either DTR
(DDR) mode -- 8 bits per CK_QSPI tick, datasheet ceiling 90 MHz
which gives 720 Mbps theoretical -- or raising CK_QSPI past PLL4's
current 656 MHz. Neither is attempted in this chapter.

== Test plan

Two blocks. First runs the proven 1-lane mission point; second
runs the proven quad mission point. Both reuse `spi_1lane.bin` /
`spi_quad.bin` built by build/spi/, symlinked into this chapter's
build directory (see Makefile). The `bench_mcu:reset_dut` pulses
D13 and the firmware-baked DFU+flash flow takes ~2.5 s to land on
the QSPI cli prompt; the `delay ms=2500` matches the proven
spi_quad timing.

The 1-lane block uses the auto-consume stream (`A` command,
auto-consume on, ping-pong DDR ~16 MiB chunks) which routes
through `cmd_auto_stream` ->
`stream_direct_crc_eligible(quad=0, raw=1) && auto_consume` ->
`stream_direct_crc_read` -> `qspi_mdma_crc_read`. The quad block
uses the twin-DDR command (`T` command, two consecutive
`qspi_mdma_read` reads into ping-pong DDR slots, byte-compare).
firsterr=-1 means pass-1 == pass-2 byte-for-byte, which proves the
channel transports the same varying byte stream identically twice
-- the mission criterion of "real varying data" without any
constant-byte short-cut.

<<TEST.md>>=
1-lane mission: 32 MiB stream at presc=5 sshift=1 expecting wall_rate >= 100 Mbps and firsterr=-1.

```
fpga.hx1k:program bin=@spi_1lane.bin
bench_mcu:reset_dut  # blobs: @main.stm32 (referenced from flash.tsv)
delay ms=2500
dfu.evb:flash_layout layout=@flash.tsv no_reconnect=true
mp135.evb:uart_open
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="JEDEC ID:" timeout_ms=10000
delay ms=300
mp135.evb:uart_write data="p 5 1\r"
delay ms=100
mp135.evb:uart_write data="a 1\r"
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="auto=on" timeout_ms=3000
mark tag=bench_start
mp135.evb:uart_write data="A 33554432 0 1\r"
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="stream_xfer 33554432 B" timeout_ms=15000
mark tag=bench_done
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel=", firsterr=-1" timeout_ms=15000
mp135.evb:uart_close
```

- Check 1-lane mission stream presc=5 sshift=1 wall_rate >= 100 Mbps firsterr=-1

Quad mission: 16 MiB twin-DDR at presc=3 sshift=0 expecting pass1_rate >= 200 Mbps and firsterr=-1.

```
fpga.hx1k:program bin=@spi_quad.bin
bench_mcu:reset_dut  # blobs: @main.stm32 (referenced from flash.tsv)
delay ms=2500
dfu.evb:flash_layout layout=@flash.tsv no_reconnect=true
mp135.evb:uart_open
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="JEDEC ID:" timeout_ms=10000
delay ms=300
mp135.evb:uart_write data="p 3 0\r"
delay ms=200
mark tag=bench_start
mp135.evb:uart_write data="T 16777216\r"
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="twin_pass1_done" timeout_ms=120000
mark tag=bench_done
mp135.evb:uart_expect sentinel="twin 16777216 B quad raw" timeout_ms=120000
mp135.evb:uart_close
```

- Check quad mission twin-DDR presc=3 sshift=0 pass1_rate >= 200 Mbps firsterr=-1
